<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-320-530  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 320 530.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  May 29 1989 v6 n21 p27(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Problems continue to postpone the information age. (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pearce, Alan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Federal Communications Commission's (FCC's) policy-makingagenda is dominated by the Open Network Architecture filings ofregional Bell holding companies, but the ONA plans will not beapproved until 1990.andP;  One of the problems with which the RBOCsmust deal is the FCC's criticism of their lack of uniformity.andO;RBOCs also want market analysis information from enhanced serviceproviders, and they must themselves provide operationalinformation to the enhanced service providers for billingpurposes.andP;  Competitive tension, state and federal regulatoryconflicts, and the restrictions of the Modified Final Judgementare other issues which some of the filings address.andP;  Threevacancies in the FCC may further slow the process of evaluation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Bell Regional Holding CompaniesInformation ServicesUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionGovernment Regulation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>